'''Ōmatono Tsunoten Tenjin Shrine''' (おおまとのつのてんじんしゃ; also read おおまとのつのあまつかみのやしろ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in {{ill|lt=Ōmaru (Inagi City)|Q30923766|WD=Q30923766|lt=Ōmaru|1=Ōmaru}}, {{ill|lt=Inagi City|Q317847|WD=Q317847|1=Inagi}}, {{ill|lt=Tokyo Metropolis|Q1490|WD=Q1490|1=Tokyo}}. Its former shrine rank was {{ill|lt=Gōsha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
; Main sanctuary
* {{ill|lt=Kushimachi no Mikoto|Q108039939|WD=Q108039939|1=Kushimachi no Mikoto}} (くしまちのみこと)
: A deity said to be the father of Ame-no-Sokotachi no Mikoto<ref name="watarai">Junzaburō Hayakawa, “Watarai-shi Keizu,” *Keizu Sōran*, vol. 2, Kokushokankōkai, 1915, p. 396.</ref>. In the *Engishiki Jinmyōchō*, the entry for the Ame-no-Kagu-yama-ni-masu Kushimachi no Mikoto Shrine in {{ill|lt=Tōichi District|Q11405036|WD=Q11405036|1=Toichi district}}, {{ill|lt=Yamato Province|Q907495|WD=Q907495|1=Yamato Province}} (present-day {{ill|lt=Amekaguyama Shrine|Q98082987|WD=Q98082987|1=Amanokaguyama Shrine}}, located on the northern foothills of {{ill|lt=Mt. Amekaguyama|Q11443780|WD=Q11443780|1=Mount Amanokagu}} in {{ill|lt=Kashihara City|Q496319|WD=Q496319|1=Kashihara, Nara}}, Nara Prefecture) includes the note “former name: Ōmatonochi no Kami.” From this, it has been considered that this shrine enshrines the same deity as Amekaguyama Shrine. Until the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, the shrine was called Marumiya Myōjin, which is said to be a corruption of “Matono-no-miya Myōjin”{{sfn|Shinpen Musashi Fudoki-kō Ōmaru Village}}.

=== History ===
[[Image:Torii of Oomatono Tsunoten Shinto Shrine in Inagi taken in May 2009.jpg|thumb|180px|Torii gate (May 2009)]]
[[Image:Komainu in Oomatono Tsunoten Shinto Shrine in Inagi taken in May 2009.jpg|thumb|180px|Komainu. Inscribed “An auspicious day in the sixth month of the twelfth year of {{ill|lt=Tenpō|Q1369045|WD=Q1369045|1=Tenpō}}, {{ill|lt=Kanoto-ushi|Q904956|WD=Q904956|1=Yin Metal Ox}}” ({{ill|lt=1841|Q7622|WD=Q7622|1=1841}}). (May 2009)]]
[[Image:View from Oomatono Tsunoten Shinto Shrine in Inagi taken in May 2009.jpg|thumb|180px|View from the precincts over the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=alluvial plain|1=UNKNOWN}} of the middle reaches of the {{ill|lt=Tama River|Q1063006|WD=Q1063006|1=Tama River}}. {{ill|lt=Inagi Bridge|Q11596545|WD=Q11596545|1=Inagi Bridge}} can be seen spanning the Tama River. (May 2009)]]
Although it is a very small shrine and its origins are unclear, the *{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Report on Shikinaisha Investigations|1=UNKNOWN}}* identifies this shrine as the “Ōmatono Tsunoten Tenjin Shrine” listed in the *{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}* for {{ill|lt=Tama District|Q11430789|WD=Q11430789|1=Tama district}}, {{ill|lt=Musashi Province|Q907398|WD=Q907398|1=Musashi Province}}. However, regarding the Shikinaisha Ōmatono Tsunoten Tenjin Shrine, {{ill|lt=Musashi Mitake Shrine|Q6587276|WD=Q6587276|1=Musashi-Mitake Shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Ōme City|Q237683|WD=Q237683|1=Ōme, Tokyo}}, Tokyo, is also considered a {{ill|lt=theoretical identification|Q135022904|WD=Q135022904|1=Shikinai Ronsha}}, and in the early {{ill|lt=Meiji era|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} Musashi Mitake Shrine was known as Ōmatono Tsunoten Tenjin Shrine.

The name “Ōmatono-tsu” is thought to mean “a landing place on a large, round, flat plain”<ref>Inagi City Board of Education (ed.), *Inagi no Chimei to Kyūdō*, p. 73.</ref>. In fact, the former place name of the lowland in front of {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Fumon Zen’an|1=UNKNOWN}} adjacent to the shrine precincts was “Irigata,” and it was a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=lagoon|1=UNKNOWN}} of the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Old Tama River|1=UNKNOWN}} sandwiched between Tenjin-yama and Shiro-yama (which contains remains of a {{ill|lt=Muromachi period|Q334845|WD=Q334845|1=Muromachi period}} fort).

The place name Ōmaru in Inagi City, where this shrine stands, is also said to mean “large, round, flat plain.” This area has been one of the river-crossing points of the {{ill|lt=Tama River|Q1063006|WD=Q1063006|1=Tama River}} since ancient times (where the {{ill|lt=Fuchū Highway|Q11486060|WD=Q11486060|1=Fuchū Highway}} and the Kawasaki Highway converge), so it is reasonable to think that there was a {{ill|lt=river port|Q11555884|WD=Q11555884|1=river port}} here. Incidentally, the aforementioned Shiro-yama is also thought to have been built to control the Tama River crossing.

