=== On-site information ===
;Address
* 847 {{ill|lt=Ōmaru (Inagi City)|Q30923766|WD=Q30923766|lt=Ōmaru|1=Ōmaru}}, {{ill|lt=Inagi City|Q317847|WD=Q317847|1=Inagi}}, {{ill|lt=Tokyo Metropolis|Q1490|WD=Q1490|1=Tokyo}}

;Access
* Nearest station: About an 8-minute walk (approx. 600 m south) from {{ill|lt=Minami-Tama Station|Q5366901|WD=Q5366901|1=Minami-Tama Station}} on the JR {{ill|lt=Nambu Line|Q1366263|WD=Q1366263|1=Nambu Line}}

;Surroundings
Located on the northern edge of the central {{ill|lt=Tama Hills|Q1502721|WD=Q1502721|1=Tama Hills}}, the shrine offers a panoramic view from its precincts of the {{ill|lt=Tama River lowland|Q131910796|WD=Q131910796|lt=alluvial plain of the middle reaches of the Tama River|1=alluvial plain of the middle reaches of the Tama River}}. The wooded hill behind the precincts was formerly called Shiro-yama; in the medieval period, a mountain castle known as Ōmaru Castle, a {{ill|lt=yamajiro|Q15710038|WD=Q15710038|1=Hill castle}}, was built there. Today, the area forms part of the {{ill|lt=Tama New Town|Q7680510|WD=Q7680510|1=Tama New Town}} {{ill|lt=Kōyōdai (Inagi City)|Q11416047|WD=Q11416047|lt=Kōyōdai|1=Kōyōdai}} residential district. Along both sides of the approach to the shrine are the Buddhist temples Enshō-ji and Jikishin-an, and to the north of the precincts is another Buddhist temple, Fumon Zen’an.

